```java
public interface IDepartment {  // Interface to hide the delegation of department management  
    String getManager();     // Getter method for manager name, hidden from outside world.
}                            

public class Department implements IDepartment{      // Implementation hiding delegate in this new implementation (Departments)       

  private final String manager;                    // Private field to store the department's Manager Name  

 public Department(String manager){                // Constructor with parameter for setting initial value of 'manager'.   
       super();                                   // Calling parent class constructor. (Departments)     
        this.manager = manager ;                   // Initializing private field ‘Manager’ by calling the argument passed to method and assign it a new instance variable named Manager .  
 }                                                 

 public String getManager(){                       // Implemented interface's Getter Method (hidden from outside world).   
       return this.manager;                      // Returning private field ' manager '.  This is the only way to access and modify it, thus hiding delegate in our Department implementation .  
 }                                                 

 public void setManager(String new_name){        // Implemented interface's Setter Method (hidden from outside world).   
       this.manager = new_name;                 // Assigning the parameter to private field ' manager '.  This is only way of modifying it, thus hiding delegate in our Department implementation .  
 }                                                 
}    
```                                                                                           
In above code: `IDepartment` interface and its implementations are hidden from outside world. Only methods defined by this interfaces can be accessed or modified within the class itself (i.e., only through these implemented classes). This is a form of abstraction in object-oriented programming, where we hide complex details about an implementation behind simple APIs that clients use to interact with it instead of directly using its internals.

